4.8.4.d: As p increases, the fraction of observations near any point goes to 0. 4.8.4.e: For p = 1, it would be 0.1. When p = 2, it would be (0.1)^(1/2) = 0.316 When p = 100, it comes out to (0.1)^(1/100) = 0.977 As p increases, length becomes closer to 1.

4.8.12.a:

Log odds of orange vs.apple in my model is \(\beta + \beta_1x\) (please imagine there being hats over the betas. I cant get the latex to work).

4.8.12.b: Log odds of orange vs.apple in my friends model is (alpha_orange0 - alpha_apple0) + (alpha_orange1 - alpha_orange1)x. (alphas have hats).

4.8.12.c: (alpha_orange0 - alpha_apple0) = 2 (alpha_orange1 - alpha_orange1) = -1

4.8.12.d: (1.2-3) = -1.8. This is for beta 0 hat. (-2-0.6) = -2.6. This is for beta 1 hat.

4.8.12.e: They should agree all the time because your friends coefficients are just reparameterizations of your own coefficients.
